[2]
Date: Mon, 27 Oct 2003 07:02:05 -1000
From: Alan Tice <alantice@idlinks.com>

In response to the message about _S. aureus_ infections related to
seawater in Florida, I would like to share our experience in Hawaii.
More than 10 years ago an association was noted between _S. aureus_
cellulitis and infections of skin wounds acquired during recreational
ocean sports such as swimming and paddling (1, 2). This was
investigated with sampling of seawater at a variety of beaches under
the direction of Roger Fujioka in the microbiology department at the
University of Hawaii (3). He found up to 100 colonies of _S. aureus_
could be recovered from some of the most popular and busy beaches at
peak-use times. The colony counts dropped rapidly at night when the
swimmers left the water and were considerably lower in the water
tested at less popular beaches.
We have recently sampled some beaches again and have found 3 strains
of MRSA -- which comprise about 1 percent of _S. aureus_ strains
recovered. This is roughly the percentage of patients carrying MRSA
when cultured at a local ambulatory care clinic (4). We are also
working to refine our methodology for ocean water sampling with
selective media and have submitted an abstract for the International
Ocean Health conference to be held here in February.
_S. aureus_ has been recovered from the seawater of a number of
countries and is thought to play a role in human disease -- in fact,
it is used as a water quality indicator (5-7). It has also been
recovered from fresh water and swimming pools, where it has a high
tolerance to chlorine (8-10). There were proposals to use _S. aureus_
as an indicator of water purity in the United States as early as 1964
(11), but the role it plays and whether it would add anything to the
established markers, such as coliform counts and enterococci, has not
been clear.
It is interesting to note that _S. aureus_ or very similar strains
have been recovered from marine mammals -- apparently unrelated to
captivity and obviously not related to hospital care (12).
It may also be of note that the PEW Oceans Commission has declared
"America's oceans are in crisis and the stakes could not be higher."
<http://www.pewoceans.org>. The CDC has also established a website
on healthy swimming that deals with fresh as well as sea water
problems <http://www.cdc.gov/healthyswimming>.
1. Chang WJ, Pien FD. Marine-acquired infections: hazards of the
ocean environment. Postgrad Med. 1986; 80: 30-33.
2. Charoenca N, Fukjioka RS. Association of staphylococcal infections
and swimming. Wat Sci Tech 1995: 31:11-17.
3. Charoenca N, Fujioka RS. Assessment of staphylococcus bacteria in
Hawaii marine recreational waters. Wat Sci Tech. 1993:27:283-289.
4. Kenner J, O'Connor T, Piantanida N, et al. Rates of carriage of
methicillin-resistant and methicillin-susceptible Staphylococcus
aureus in an outpatient population. Infect Control Hosp Epidemiol.
2003;24:439-444.
5. Yoshpe-Purer Y, Goderman S. Occurrence of Staphylococcus aureus
and Pseudomonas aeruginosa in Israeli coastal water. Appl Environ
Microbiol. 1987;53:1138-41.
6. Cheung WHS, Chang KCK, Hung RPS. Effects of beach water pollution
in Hong Kong. Epidemiol Infect 1989; 105:139-162.
7. deAraujo MA, Guimaraes VF, Mendonca-Hagler LCS, et al.
Staphylococcus aureus and fecal streptococci in fresh and marine
waters of Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. Revista de Microbiologia.
1990;21:141-147.
8. Diaper JP, Edwards C. Survival of Staphylococcus aureus in lake
water monitored by flo cytometry. Microbiology. 1994; 140:35-42.
9. Rivera JB, Adera T. Assessing Water Quality. Staphylococci as
microbial indicators of swimming pools. J Environ Health.
1991;53:29-32.
10. Keirn MA, Putnam HD. Resistance of staphylococci to halogens as
related to a swimming pool environment. Health Lab Sci.
1968;5:180-193.
11. Favero MS, Drake CH, Randall GB. Use of staphylococi as indicator
of swimming pool pollution. Pub Health Rep 1964;79:61
12. Palmer CJ. Bacteriological and serological studies of bottlenose
dolphins. PhD dissertation 1989. University of Hawaii at Manoa,
Honolulu, Hawaii.
--
Alan D Tice, MD
John A Burns School of Medicine, University of Hawaii
Honolulu, Hawaii
<alantice@idlinks.com>
